Windowed centroids in SEP have a tendency to walk away from the target in
cases where a brighter neighbor is present. SExtractor suffers from the same
behavior but has an internal kill switch that halts the iteration process when
the centroid has walked too far. In that case, SE returns the standard centroid
(lower precision).

Using SEP, I believe a middle ground is possible (and preferable) where the
analysis and iteration is restricted to pixels that are part of the detection.
This should exclude most flux from nearby neighbors. There are a number of
ways to implement such a scheme and the 'easy' way might have poor performance.

In this investigation I will:
(a) implement this restricted windowing scheme using the 'mask' parameter
(b) assess whether it prevents the walk-away-to-neighbor phenomenon
(c) measure how much slower it is to run a separate mask on each target
(d) using a working implementation, demonstrate with synthetic PSFs that the
result is actually an improvement

Basic workflow will be copied from my existing easy_sep module. I have chosen
a typical J-band image (wircam_J_1325839p.fits.fz) as the test case.

